{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01X3PD8puqLWtFhBySva4m5x","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# nginx-ingress/renew_tls_secret\n2\t#\n3\t# An Ingress for {{params.host}} has TLS enabled with an expired leaf\n4\t# certificate. The agent must renew the TLS secret so HTTPS requests\n5\t# succeed. The CA remains unchanged.\n6\t\n7\tparams:\n8\t  host:\n9\t    default: demo.example.com\n10\t    description: Hostname served over HTTPS by the TLS-enabled Ingress.\n11\t  curl_pod_name:\n12\t    default: curl-test\n13\t    description: Name of the in-cluster pod used to issue test requests.\n14\t  expected_body:\n15\t    default: hello\n16\t    description: Response body the backend returns on success.\n17\t\n18\tprompt: |\n19\t  An Ingress resource exists for {{params.host}} with TLS enabled.\n20\t  HTTPS traffic to this domain is failing with certificate validation\n21\t  errors. The application backend is healthy and responding correctly.\n22\t\n23\t  To test the ingress from inside the cluster, use the {{params.curl_pod_name}} pod:\n24\t  ```bash\n25\t  source /tmp/ingress_env\n26\t  kubectl -n demo exec {{params.curl_pod_name}} -- /tmp/test_ingress.sh \\\n27\t    $INGRESS_HTTPS_PORT $INGRESS_NODE_IP {{params.host}}\n28\t  ```\n29\t\n30\t  Or directly with curl:\n31\t  ```bash\n32\t  source /tmp/ingress_env\n33\t  kubectl -n demo exec {{params.curl_pod_name}} -- sh -c \\\n34\t    'curl -v --cacert /tmp/tls/ca.crt \\\n35\t      --resolve {{params.host}}:'\"$INGRESS_HTTPS_PORT\"':'\"$INGRESS_NODE_IP\"' \\\n36\t      https://{{params.host}}:'\"$INGRESS_HTTPS_PORT\"'/'\n37\t  ```\n38\t\n39\t  Note: use the CA override (--cacert /tmp/tls/ca.crt) for validation.\n40\t  openssl is available via the toolbox pod:\n41\t  ```bash\n42\t  kubectl -n demo exec openssl-toolbox -- openssl version\n43\t  ```\n44\t\n45\t  Diagnose the TLS issue and restore HTTPS access to the service.\n46\t  Success criteria: the curl command returns exit code 0 and